    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1954-04-30T16:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1954-04-30T16:00:00-05:00" n="399"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d399">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">396.1 GE/4–3054: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                            <gloss type="to">Department of State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">secret</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Geneva</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1954-04-30T22:00:00+01:00"
                            >April 30, 1954—10 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <gloss target="#t_Secto1">Secto</gloss> 54. Repeated information Paris 157,
                    Saigon 18. French advise us of receipt from <persName corresp="#p_DM1">De
                        Jean</persName> of his estimate on current overall situation. In <persName
                        corresp="#p_DM1">De Jean</persName>’s opinion it was incorrect to envisage
                    only two alternatives of internationalization of war or negotiation of
                    cease–fire with <persName corresp="#p_HCM1">Ho</persName>. Re latter, he would
                    regard anything less than <persName corresp="#p_LJ1">Laniel</persName>’s
                    conditions as calamitous.<note n="1" xml:id="d399fn1">For a report on <persName
                            corresp="#p_LJ1">Laniel</persName>’s conditions of Mar. 5, 1954, see
                        telegram 3240 from Paris, Mar. 6, <ref target="#pg_435">p. 435</ref>.</note>
                    He inclined toward increased American participation short of direct intervention
                    but felt it essential French retain top control <pb facs="0666" n="640"
                        xml:id="pg_640"/> militarily, financially and politically. He would not yet
                    admit fall Dien Bien Phu inevitable but felt that its fall would have very
                    serious repercussions on Vietnamese military and civilian morale. He also felt
                    that longer Geneva discussions continued, the worse would be effect on
                    Vietnamese opinion.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_DJF1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Dulles</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
